<p>
<p>We predict Y from X1 using linear regression analysis. The Pearson correlation between X1 and Y is r = 0.40 and <span class="math inline">\(s_Y^2\)</span> = 100. When we add a second variable, X2, to the regression model we get <span class="math inline">\(R^2\)</span> = 0.25. How much additional variance is explained by the addition of X2 compared to the regression model with only X1?</p>
</p>]]></text>
</questiontext>
<generalfeedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
</p>]]></text>
</generalfeedback>
<penalty>0</penalty>
<defaultgrade>1</defaultgrade>
